aped the dominant thinking within the state and the military. There are equally important studies of sensitive topics like the political economy of the state and the level of human security in the country. The three major ethnic groups in the country — Karen, Kachin, and Shan — are also studied in detail. Some of the negotiations between the Karen and Kachin ethnic insurgent group representatives on the one hand, and the military junta on the other, are spelled out in detail. An important corollary finding is the importance of religion and religious personalities in brokering peace between the ethnic groups and the military government. Finally, the book deals with how the various ethnic groups are trying to cope with decades of conflict and reconstruct their communities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEthnicityzBurma. 0aEthnicity--Burma. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Demography.2bisacsh1 aGanesan, N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGanesan, N., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHlaing, Kyaw Yin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLahtaw, Ja Nan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMong, Sai Kham, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNemoto, Kei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSafman, Rachel M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSaw, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSteinberg, David I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaylor, Robert H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThan, Tin Maung Maung, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWin, Khin Zaw, econtributo